r=Feral House |isbn=978-1-936239-75-7}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Pattison |editor1-first=Louis |editor2-last=Richardson |editor2-first=Nick |editor3-last=Stosuy |editor3-first=Brandon |title=Black Metal: Beyond the Darkness |url=http://blackdogonline.com/music/black-metal.html |year=2012 |publisher=Black Dog Publishing |isbn=978-1-907317-72-9 |access-date=16 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512002827/http://blackdogonline.com/music/black-metal.html |archive-date=12 May 2013 |url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite book |last=Swinford |first=Dean |year=2013 |title=Death Metal Epic (Book I: The Inverted Katabasis) |location=Dayton |publisher=Atlatl Press |isbn=978-0-9883484-3-1}}\n\n{{Heavy metal music}}\n{{Extreme metal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Metal}}\n[[Category:Black metal| ]]\n[[Category:European culture]]\n[[Category:20th-century music genres]]\n[[Category:1980s in music]]\n[[Category:1990s in music]]\n[[Category:2000s in music]]\n[[Category:2010s in music]]\n[[Category:21st-century music genres]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal genres]]\n[[Category:Extreme metal]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Norwegian styles of music]]\n[[Category:British rock music genres]]\n", "name_user": "Harvigrimnir", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences in media)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_metal"}
{"title_page": "Laurie Patton (Australian executive)", "text_new": "{{multiple|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2019}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=December 2019}}\n{{Autobiography|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Laurie Patton.jpeg|thumb|Laurie Patton]] -->[[File:Laurie Patton.jpg|thumb|Laurie Patton]]\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n'''Laurie Patton''' is an [[Australia]]n public interest advocacy and communications practitioner, social commentator,<ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/120312-op-ed-we-wouldnt-need-inquiries-if-public-administration-wasnt-so-broken/</ref><ref>https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/</ref> and a former journalist and media executive. He is currently Vice-President of the [[Telecommunications Society of Australia]] (TelSoc).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itwire.com/business-technology/australia-%E2%80%9Cfalling-behind%E2%80%9D-apac-in-developing-technologies,-says-telsoc-chief.html |title=Australia 'falling behind' APAC in developing technologies, says Telsoc chief |publisher=iTWire |date=2019-12-03 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Telsoc {{!}} Telsoc |url=https://telsoc.org/about |website=telsoc.org |publisher=Telsoc |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/</ref>\n==Career==\nNow active in the [[non-profit]] sector Patton is a former CEO / Executive Director of [[Internet Australia]],<ref>https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour]</ref><ref>https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187</ref> the peak body representing the interests of Internet users and a chapter of the global [[Internet Society]], where he initiated an ongoing campaign for #BetterBroadband.<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband</ref><ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/</ref><ref>https://www.itwire.com/strategy/patton-calls-for-govt-to-fund-nbn-co-to-employ-those-retrenched-due-to-covit-19-crisis.html</ref><ref>https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2020/is-now-the-time-to-fix-the-nbn-.html</ref>\n\nShortly after joining Internet Australia Patton told a parliamentary inquiry the drafting of the controversial Date Retention Act ([[Telecommunications (Interception and Access) Amendment (Data Retention) Act 2015]]) was \"a monumental stuff-up\" and \u201cfundamentally flawed\u201d.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group</ref><ref>https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates</ref> He subsequently commented on matters such as digital literacy, broadband policy,<ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398</ref><ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376]</ref><ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/</ref> and the media.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546</ref>\n\nPatton is a former executive at the [[Seven Network]].<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven?rq=laurie%20patton</ref><ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie+Patton</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/</ref> He created the [[World Movies]] Pay-TV channel<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven?rq=laurie%20patton</ref><ref>https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187</ref> and was founding CEO of community station TVS ([[Television Sydney]]).<ref>https://www.if.com.au/tvs-laurie-patton-signs-off/</ref>\n\nPatton has held for-profit and non-profit board roles, including at the [[National Heart Foundation of Australia]]<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf</ref> and the NSW Film & Television Office (now [[Screen NSW]]).<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/main/About_us/NSW-Annual-Report.pd</ref> As deputy chair of the FTO he initiated and led the first official Australian delegation to the Shanghai International Film Festival.<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article</ref><ref>https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf</ref>\nHe was a member of an expert panel for a review of the Indigenous broadcasting and media sector for the Australian Government.<ref>https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf</ref>\n\nSince joining TelSoc Patton has continued to campaign for repair of the [[National Broadband Network]] (NBN)<ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/</ref> and has advocated the allocation of government [[Coronavirus]] stimulous funding for the employment of retrenched workers to be deployed to upgrade the NBN.<ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/theprojecttv/status/1241631118920765441?s=21</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2020/04/06/nbn-digital-divide-australia/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://theluckygeneral.biz The Lucky General]'', Laurie Patton's blog\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2019}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=December 2019}}\n{{Autobiography|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Laurie Patton.jpeg|thumb|Laurie Patton]] -->[[File:Laurie Patton.jpg|thumb|Laurie Patton]]\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n'''Laurie Patton''' is an [[Australia]]n public interest advocacy and communications practitioner, social commentator,<ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/120312-op-ed-we-wouldnt-need-inquiries-if-public-administration-wasnt-so-broken/</ref><ref>https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/</ref> and a former journalist and media executive. He is currently Vice-President of the [[Telecommunications Society of Australia]] (TelSoc).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itwire.com/business-technology/australia-%E2%80%9Cfalling-behind%E2%80%9D-apac-in-developing-technologies,-says-telsoc-chief.html |title=Australia 'falling behind' APAC in developing technologies, says Telsoc chief |publisher=iTWire |date=2019-12-03 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Telsoc {{!}} Telsoc |url=https://telsoc.org/about |website=telsoc.org |publisher=Telsoc |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/</ref>\n==Career==\nNow active in the [[non-profit]] sector Patton is a former CEO / Executive Director of [[Internet Australia]],<ref>https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour]</ref><ref>https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187</ref> the peak body representing the interests of Internet users and a chapter of the global [[Internet Society]], where he initiated an ongoing campaign for #BetterBroadband.<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband</ref><ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/</ref><ref>https://www.itwire.com/strategy/patton-calls-for-govt-to-fund-nbn-co-to-employ-those-retrenched-due-to-covit-19-crisis.html</ref><ref>https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2020/is-now-the-time-to-fix-the-nbn-.html</ref>\n\nShortly after joining Internet Australia Patton told a parliamentary inquiry the drafting of the controversial Date Retention Act ([[Telecommunications (Interception and Access) Amendment (Data Retention) Act 2015]]) was \"a monumental stuff-up\" and \u201cfundamentally flawed\u201d.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group</ref><ref>https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669</ref><ref>https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates</ref> He subsequently commented on matters such as digital literacy, broadband policy,<ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398</ref><ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376]</ref><ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/</ref> and the media.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546</ref>\n\nPatton is a former executive at the [[Seven Network]].<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven?rq=laurie%20patton</ref><ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie+Patton</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/</ref><ref>https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/</ref> He created the [[World Movies]] Pay-TV channel<ref>https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven?rq=laurie%20patton</ref><ref>https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187</ref> and was founding CEO of community station TVS ([[Television Sydney]]).<ref>https://www.if.com.au/tvs-laurie-patton-signs-off/</ref>\n\nPatton has held for-profit and non-profit board roles, including at the [[National Heart Foundation of Australia]]<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf</ref> and the NSW Film & Television Office (now [[Screen NSW]]).<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/main/About_us/NSW-Annual-Report.pd</ref> As deputy chair of the FTO he initiated and led the first official Australian delegation to the Shanghai International Film Festival.<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article</ref><ref>https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf</ref>\nHe was a member of an expert panel for a review of the Indigenous broadcasting and media sector for the Australian Government.<ref>https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf</ref>\n\nSince joining TelSoc Patton has continued to campaign for repair of the [[National Broadband Network]] (NBN)<ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/</ref> and has advocated the allocation of government [[Coronavirus]] stimulous funding for the employment of retrenched workers to be deployed to upgrade the NBN.<ref>https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/theprojecttv/status/1241631118920765441?s=21</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://theluckygeneral.biz The Lucky General]'', Laurie Patton's blog\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian bloggers]]\n", "name_user": "Edit0695", "label": "safe", "comment": "COI. Added another reference.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurie_Patton_(Australian_executive)"}
{"title_page": "RELIEF Act of 2019", "text_new": "The '''Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families (RELIEF) Act of 2019''' ([https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603 S.2603]) is a proposed [[Immigration reform in the US|immigration reform]] bill introduced by Sen. [[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois|IL]]) in the [[United States Senate]] on October 16, 2019. The bill seeks to amend the [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationality Act]] to end the immigrant visa backlog.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603/text|title=Text - S.2603 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families Act|last=Durbin|first=Richard J.|date=2019-10-16|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox United States federal proposed legislation|name=RELIEF Act|fullname=Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families Act of 2019|acronym=RELIEF Act|nickname=The \"green card bill\", the \"per-country cap bill\".|introduced in the=116th|introduced on=October 16, 2019|sponsored by=[[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois (state)|IL]])|number of co-sponsors=6 in the [[United States Senate]].|public law url=|cite public law=|cite statutes at large=|acts affected=[[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationality Act]].|acts repealed=|title affected=|sections created=|sections affected={{USC|8|1101}}, {{USC|8|1151}}, {{USC|8|1152}}, {{USC|8|1153}}, {{USC|8|1154}}, {{USC|8|1157}}, {{USC|8|1182}}, {{USC|8|1184}}, {{USC|8|1186}}, {{USC|8|1201}}, {{USC|8|1255}}.|agenciesaffected=[[Department of Homeland Security]], [[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]].|authorizationsofappropriations=|appropriations=|leghisturl=|introducedin=Senate|introducedbill=[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603: S.2603]|introducedby=[[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois (state)|IL]])|introduceddate=October 16, 2019|committees=[[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]|passedbody1=|passeddate1=|passedvote1=|passedbody2=|passeddate2=|passedvote2=|conferencedate=|passedbody3=|passeddate3=|passedvote3=|agreedbody3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreeddate3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreedvote3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreedbody4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|agreeddate4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|agreedvote4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|passedbody4=|passeddate4=|passedvote4=|signedpresident=|signeddate=|amendments=}}\n\n== Introduction ==\nThe [[Immigration Act of 1990]] established five occupational categories (in the [[Immigration Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationalities Act of 1965]] only two existed). It provided 140,000 immigrant visas ([[Green card|green cards]]) annually for employment-based immigration and mandated that foreign nationals of no country shall receive more than 7% of the available visas in each category in any given year, with the exception of excess unused visas. However, this is not the case for the [[H-1B visa]] system. As such, Indian nationals that for years have received the majority of H-1B visas,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/sites/default/files/USCIS/Resources/Reports%20and%20Studies/Immigration%20Forms%20Data/BAHA/h-1b-2007-2017-trend-tables.pdf|title=Number of H-1B Petition Filings FY2007 - FY2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.uscis.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> despite receiving about 20% of the annual Employment-based green cards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/dam/visas/Statistics/AnnualReports/FY2018AnnualReport/FY18AnnualReport%20-%20TableV.pdf|title=Immigrant Visas Issued and Adjustments of Status Subject to Numerical Limitations Fiscal Year 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=www.travel.state.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/immigration-statistics/yearbook|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics|date=2009-07-09|website=Department of Homeland Security|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> have to wait decades before receiving one. A similar situation holds for immigrants applying for family-based green cards where millions of people, mostly from the Philippines, Mexico, India, and China, have to wait years before receiving a green card. The fundamental cause of the green card backlog is that annual demand for green cards is much higher than ones available annually and not, as some may assume, the per-country caps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@goodarzm/what-are-the-implications-of-the-fairness-for-high-skilled-immigrants-act-of-2019-e8dce7b2ab6d|title=What are the Implications of the \u201cFairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act of 2019\u201d (H.R.1044/S.386)?|last=Mehr|first=Goodarz|date=2019-08-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> It is estimated that currently there are 4.7 million people waiting in the green card backlog, 3.9 million of whom are waiting for a family-based green card and the rest waiting for an employment-based green card.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/policy-analysis/immigration-wait-times-quotas-have-doubled-green-card-backlogs-are-long|title=Immigration Wait Times from Quotas Have Doubled: Green Card Backlogs Are Long, Growing, and Inequitable|date=2019-06-18|website=Cato Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> \n\n== Provisions ==\nThe bill would, after a five-year transition period, remove the per-country caps for employment-based green cards and increase the per-country caps for family-sponsored green cards from 7% to 15%, while increasing the number of total available green cards. Specifically, this bill would do the following.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cato.org/blog/senate-democrats-relief-act-would-double-legal-immigration-over-10-years|title=Senate Democrats\u2019 RELIEF Act Would Double Legal Immigration Over 10 Years|date=2019-10-18|website=Cato Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.durbin.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/durbin-leahy-introduce-new-legislation-to-increase-number-of-green-cards-available-eliminating-the-backlog|title=Durbin, Leahy Introduce New Legislation To Increase Number Of Green Cards Available, Eliminating The Backlog {{!}} U.S. Senator Dick Durbin of Illinois|website=www.durbin.senate.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n* Over a five-year transition period, it would phase out the per-country numerical limits on employment-based green cards and increase the per-country limits on family-sponsored green cards from 7% to 15%.\n* It would create a pool of new green cards almost equal to the entire number of people in the employment- and family-based backlogs, and would distribute those in a course of five years.\n* It would uncap the family-sponsored second preference F-2A category for new spouses and minor children of existing legal permanent residents in the United States, which has a cap of about 88,000 and backlog of about 150,000.\n* It would increases the number of green cards for the family-sponsored first preference category from 23,400 to 111,334, essentially reassigning the 88,000 from the F-2A category.\n* It would exempt derivatives (spouses and minor children) of primary applicants from numerical limits.\n* It would protect \u201caging out\u201d children who qualify for legal permanent resident status based on a parent\u2019s immigration petition.\n\n== Viewpoint of Third Parties ==\nThe bill has received the backing of several organizations, including [[American Immigration Lawyers Association]] (AILA); immigration advocacy groups such as [https://www.supallofus.org/ Support Alliance of US Immigrants], [https://unitedwedream.org/ United We Dream], [https://ucausa.org/ United Chinese Americans]; and professional organizations such as [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (IEEE) and [[National Association of Graduate-Professional Students]] (NAGPS).<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aila.org/File/Related/19101805a.pdf|title=Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families (RELIEF) Act|last=|first=|date=October 18, 2019|website=www.aila.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supallofus.org/|title=Support Alliance of US Immigrants|website=Support All of Us|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ieee-usa-supports-the-relief-act-to-clear-immigration-backlog-300940662.html|title=IEEE-USA Supports the RELIEF Act to Clear Immigration Backlog|last=IEEE-USA|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> They note that, unlike other legislation such as the Fairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act, this bill is a win-win since it both makes the immigration system more fair by eliminating or raising the per-country caps, and eliminates the backlog by increasing the number of available green cards.<ref name=\":1\" /> They argue that since immigrants impacted by this policy already have jobs here, no American jobs would be affected. Furthermore, by eliminating the backlog it would allow the United States to retain the international talent that studies in its institutes of higher education.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the other hand, the bill has received pushback from anti-immigration groups such as [https://www.ustechworkers.com/ U.S. Tech Workers] who argue that the bill does not address problems of the H-1B program and will further contribute to the displacement of American workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ustechworkers.com/sen-durbin-introduces-bad-green-card-giveaway-legislation-dismissive-of-u-s-workers/|title=Sen. Durbin Introduces Bad Green Card Giveaway Legislation, Dismissive of U.S. Workers|last=Guzzardi|first=Joe|date=2019-10-24|website=U.S. Tech Workers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n* [[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013]]\n\n* [[Immigration Act of 1990]]\n\n* [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1044 Fairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act]\n\n[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2091 BELIEVE Act]\n\n[[Category:Immigration to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families (RELIEF) Act of 2019''' ([https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603 S.2603]) is a proposed [[Immigration reform in the US|immigration reform]] bill introduced by Sen. [[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois|IL]]) in the [[United States Senate]] on October 16, 2019. The bill seeks to amend the [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationality Act]] to end the immigrant visa backlog.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603/text|title=Text - S.2603 - 116th Congress (2019-2020): Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families Act|last=Durbin|first=Richard J.|date=2019-10-16|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox United States federal proposed legislation|name=RELIEF Act|fullname=Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families Act of 2019|acronym=RELIEF Act|nickname=The \"green card bill\", the \"per-country cap bill\".|introduced in the=116th|introduced on=October 16, 2019|sponsored by=[[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois (state)|IL]])|number of co-sponsors=6 in the [[United States Senate]].|public law url=|cite public law=|cite statutes at large=|acts affected=[[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationality Act]].|acts repealed=|title affected=|sections created=|sections affected={{USC|8|1101}}, {{USC|8|1151}}, {{USC|8|1152}}, {{USC|8|1153}}, {{USC|8|1154}}, {{USC|8|1157}}, {{USC|8|1182}}, {{USC|8|1184}}, {{USC|8|1186}}, {{USC|8|1201}}, {{USC|8|1255}}.|agenciesaffected=[[Department of Homeland Security]], [[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]].|authorizationsofappropriations=|appropriations=|leghisturl=|introducedin=Senate|introducedbill=[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2603: S.2603]|introducedby=[[Dick Durbin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Illinois (state)|IL]])|introduceddate=October 16, 2019|committees=[[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]|passedbody1=|passeddate1=|passedvote1=|passedbody2=|passeddate2=|passedvote2=|conferencedate=|passedbody3=|passeddate3=|passedvote3=|agreedbody3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreeddate3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreedvote3=<!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee -->|agreedbody4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|agreeddate4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|agreedvote4=<!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation -->|passedbody4=|passeddate4=|passedvote4=|signedpresident=|signeddate=|amendments=}}\n\n== Introduction ==\nThe [[Immigration Act of 1990]] established five occupational categories (in the [[Immigration Act of 1965|Immigration and Nationalities Act of 1965]] only two existed). It provided 140,000 immigrant visas ([[Green card|green cards]]) annually for employment-based immigration and mandated that foreign nationals of no country shall receive more than 7% of the available visas in each category in any given year, with the exception of excess unused visas. However, this is not the case for the [[H-1B visa]] system. As such, Indian nationals that for years have received the majority of H-1B visas,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/sites/default/files/USCIS/Resources/Reports%20and%20Studies/Immigration%20Forms%20Data/BAHA/h-1b-2007-2017-trend-tables.pdf|title=Number of H-1B Petition Filings FY2007 - FY2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.uscis.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> despite receiving about 20% of the annual Employment-based green cards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/dam/visas/Statistics/AnnualReports/FY2018AnnualReport/FY18AnnualReport%20-%20TableV.pdf|title=Immigrant Visas Issued and Adjustments of Status Subject to Numerical Limitations Fiscal Year 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=www.travel.state.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/immigration-statistics/yearbook|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics|date=2009-07-09|website=Department of Homeland Security|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> have to wait decades before receiving one. A similar situation holds for immigrants applying for family-based green cards where millions of people, mostly from the Philippines, Mexico, India, and China, have to wait years before receiving a green card. The fundamental cause of the green card backlog is that annual demand for green cards is much higher than ones available annually and not, as some may assume, the per-country caps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@goodarzm/what-are-the-implications-of-the-fairness-for-high-skilled-immigrants-act-of-2019-e8dce7b2ab6d|title=What are the Implications of the \u201cFairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act of 2019\u201d (H.R.1044/S.386)?|last=Mehr|first=Goodarz|date=2019-08-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> It is estimated that currently there are 4.7 million people waiting in the green card backlog, 3.9 million of whom are waiting for a family-based green card and the rest waiting for an employment-based green card.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/policy-analysis/immigration-wait-times-quotas-have-doubled-green-card-backlogs-are-long|title=Immigration Wait Times from Quotas Have Doubled: Green Card Backlogs Are Long, Growing, and Inequitable|date=2019-06-18|website=Cato Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> \n\n== Provisions ==\nThe bill would, after a five-year transition period, remove the per-country caps for employment-based green cards and increase the per-country caps for family-sponsored green cards from 7% to 15%, while increasing the number of total available green cards. Specifically, this bill would do the following.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cato.org/blog/senate-democrats-relief-act-would-double-legal-immigration-over-10-years|title=Senate Democrats\u2019 RELIEF Act Would Double Legal Immigration Over 10 Years|date=2019-10-18|website=Cato Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.durbin.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/durbin-leahy-introduce-new-legislation-to-increase-number-of-green-cards-available-eliminating-the-backlog|title=Durbin, Leahy Introduce New Legislation To Increase Number Of Green Cards Available, Eliminating The Backlog {{!}} U.S. Senator Dick Durbin of Illinois|website=www.durbin.senate.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n* Over a five-year transition period, it would phase out the per-country numerical limits on employment-based green cards and increase the per-country limits on family-sponsored green cards from 7% to 15%.\n* It would create a pool of new green cards almost equal to the entire number of people in the employment- and family-based backlogs, and would distribute those in a course of five years.\n* It would uncap the family-sponsored second preference F-2A category for new spouses and minor children of existing legal permanent residents in the United States, which has a cap of about 88,000 and backlog of about 150,000.\n* It would increases the number of green cards for the family-sponsored first preference category from 23,400 to 111,334, essentially reassigning the 88,000 from the F-2A category.\n* It would exempt derivatives (spouses and minor children) of primary applicants from numerical limits.\n* It would protect \u201caging out\u201d children who qualify for legal permanent resident status based on a parent\u2019s immigration petition.\n\n== Viewpoint of Third Parties ==\nThe bill has received the backing of several organizations, including [[American Immigration Lawyers Association]] (AILA); immigration advocacy groups such as [https://www.supallofus.org/ Support Alliance of US Immigrants], [https://unitedwedream.org/ United We Dream], [https://ucausa.org/ United Chinese Americans]; and professional organizations such as [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (IEEE) and [[National Association of Graduate-Professional Students]] (NAGPS).<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aila.org/File/Related/19101805a.pdf|title=Resolving Extended Limbo for Immigrant Employees and Families (RELIEF) Act|last=|first=|date=October 18, 2019|website=www.aila.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supallofus.org/|title=Support Alliance of US Immigrants|website=Support All of Us|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ieee-usa-supports-the-relief-act-to-clear-immigration-backlog-300940662.html|title=IEEE-USA Supports the RELIEF Act to Clear Immigration Backlog|last=IEEE-USA|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> They note that, unlike other legislation such as the Fairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act, this bill is a win-win since it both makes the immigration system more fair by eliminating or raising the per-country caps, and eliminates the backlog by increasing the number of available green cards.<ref name=\":1\" /> They argue that since immigrants impacted by this policy already have jobs here, no American jobs would be affected. Furthermore, by eliminating the backlog it would allow the United States to retain the international talent that studies in its institutes of higher education.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the other hand, the bill has received pushback from anti-immigration groups such as [https://www.ustechworkers.com/ U.S. Tech Workers] who argue that the bill does not address problems of the H-1B program and will further contribute to the displacement of American workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ustechworkers.com/sen-durbin-introduces-bad-green-card-giveaway-legislation-dismissive-of-u-s-workers/|title=Sen. Durbin Introduces Bad Green Card Giveaway Legislation, Dismissive of U.S. Workers|last=Guzzardi|first=Joe|date=2019-10-24|website=U.S. Tech Workers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n[[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013]]\n\n[[Immigration Act of 1990]]\n\n[[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1044 Fairness for High-Skilled Immigrants Act]\n\n[https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/2091 BELIEVE Act]\n\n[[Category:Immigration to the United States]]\n", "name_user": "MaigoAkisame", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee Also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RELIEF_Act_of_2019"}
